{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"19653d32-5aa4-4cb2-b152-6e0739ca61d6","content":"I don't see a `.dmp` file in the current workspace. Here's how to analyze your .NET crash dump:\n\n### Recommended Tools\n\n1. **`dotnet-dump analyze <file.dmp>`** — cross-platform, easiest option\n   ```bash\n   dotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n   dotnet-dump analyze crash.dmp\n   ```\n   Useful commands inside the REPL:\n   - `clrstack` — managed call stacks\n   - `pe` — print last exception\n   - `dumpheap -stat` — heap summary\n   - `threads` — list all threads\n\n2. **WinDbg + SOS** (Windows) — most powerful option\n3. **Visual Studio** (Windows) — open the `.dmp` directly, click \"Debug with Managed Only\"\n\n### Quick Triage Steps\n\n1. Run `pe` (print exception) to find the unhandled exception\n2. Run `clrstack` to see where it crashed\n3. Run `threads` then switch to faulting thread with `setthread`\n4. Inspect locals/objects with `dumpobj`\n\n---\n\nIf you upload or place the `.dmp` file in this workspace, I can run `dotnet-dump analyze` on it directly (if it's a Linux dump). Would you like to proceed that way?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e3e9651c-9f16-486c-89d1-2a6b160822d2","outputTokens":312,"requestId":"5FC8:C532C:E69DA1:10AA12C:69EACC02"},"id":"a2c4bb9c-97e2-4f03-aa24-8f1985506dfc","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:48:59.273Z","parentId":"78b40588-823d-4c72-ad79-39cf6927caeb"}
